\section{A very informal half-baked proposal for code-coupling in FAST world}

\textbf{Remark:} More baking required.

\subsection{Thoughts/comments}

\begin{itemize}

\item This document is the start of trying to figure out a coupling
framework for FAST and FAST-related programs.  

\item The motivation is that we need to give guidance to developers to
provide interface data in a standardized manner that simplifies coupling
with other components.

\item Things to think of: units, quantities known and/or needed by a
component, directions

\item Need an approach that is general enough to explore/incorporate various
algorithmic coupling approaches

\item In some cases, intput data will be required at different locations
than those for output data.  For example, a beam finite element model solves
for dependent variables at nodes, but requires pressure values at Gauss
points.

\end{itemize}

\subsection{Geometric entitites for coupling}

Assume that the physcial interface of a componet is either one of the following
or some combination:
\begin{enumerate} 
\item a point  (e.g.  connection of a mooring line)

\item a line (e.g. a beam reprentation of a blade)

\item a surface (e.g. pressure distribution over a blade)

\item a volume (e.g. OpenFOAM finite volume)

\end{enumerate}

These four geometric entities can be well described in a standard
finite-element sense; see Figs. 1-3.  We could allow for linear and
quadratic (serendipity or standard) finite-element representations. 

\textbf{Remark:} using a finite-element representation of component
interfaces has nothing to do with the discretization used by the underlying
components.


Interface elements:

Point: point

Line (Fig. 1): two-node or three-node line elements

Suface (Fig. 2): 3/6-node triangles elements; 4/8-node quadrilateral elements

Volume (Fig. 3): 8/20-node hexahedral elements;  
6/15-node wedge-elements;
4/10-node tetrahedron elements

\textbf{Remarks:} Figs. 1-3 show a standard numbering scheme. Linear-element 
number is a subset of the quadratic-element numbering shown.

\subsection{Data-transfer info}

We wish to be able to transfer input-output properties across the coupled
interface.  This is specific to the "self" domain.  For example, say we have
a square surface definied by a single 4-node element.  The data required to
build a coupling routine could be embodied as (\# denotes a comment line).
Here we assume that output data is available at nodes, and the locations
required for input data are definined in element-level natural coordinates.
For example, for the following surface element, we want input forcing/data
at Gauss points.





\begin{verbatim}
# number of nodes
4
# node number and locations:  num, x, y, z
1 0. 0. 0.
2 1. 0. 0.
3 0. 1. 0.
4 1. 1. 0.
# number of point elements
0
# point-element definitions: number of nodes, n1, n2, ... 
# number of line elements
0
# line-element definitions: number of nodes, n1, n2, ... 
# number of surface elements
1
# surface-element definitions: number of nodes, n1, n2, ... 
4 1 2 4 3
# number of volume elements
0
# volume-element definitions: number of nodes, n1, n2, ... 

\end{verbatim}







